==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glair
<hw>Glair</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>glaire</ets>,
<ets>glaire</ets> d'<?/uf, the glair of an egg, prob. fr. L.
<ets>clarus</ets> clear, bright. See <er>Clear</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The white of egg. It is used as a size or a glaze in
bookbinding, for pastry, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any viscous, transparent substance, resembling the
white of an egg.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A broadsword fixed on a pike; a kind of
halberd.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glair
<hw>Glair</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Glaired</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Glairing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To smear with the white of an
egg.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glaire</ent>⟦br⟧
